00:01:41.000 --> 00:02:05.320
I'm super excited that we finally got you here, and we look forward to hearing you

00:02:05.320 --> 00:02:18.600
talk about programming education.

00:02:18.600 --> 00:02:20.119
Good morning, everyone.

00:02:20.119 --> 00:02:21.119
So my name is Felina.

00:02:21.119 --> 00:02:23.360
I'm an associate professor at Leiden University.

00:02:23.360 --> 00:02:24.639
I'm also on Twitter.

00:02:24.639 --> 00:02:27.320
My Twitter handle is my first name, super easy.

00:02:27.320 --> 00:02:30.679
So if you want to talk about this talk, maybe mention me so I can see what's going on in

00:02:30.679 --> 00:02:32.360
the room afterwards.

00:02:32.360 --> 00:02:37.039
So this talk is about explicit direct instruction in programming education.

00:02:37.039 --> 00:02:42.960
That sounds a bit technical, so an alternative title that we might use is one I stole from

00:02:42.960 --> 00:02:47.000
Greg Wilson of our studio is how to teach programming and other things.

00:02:47.000 --> 00:02:49.039
That's what we're really going to talk about.

00:02:49.039 --> 00:02:50.720
How do we teach programming?

00:02:50.720 --> 00:02:55.240
Because a lot of you probably are also involved to some extent in teaching.

00:02:55.240 --> 00:03:00.320
Maybe you teach your kids, but also junior colleagues, maybe on your team, you want to

00:03:00.320 --> 00:03:04.679
get them up to speed on your code base or libraries that you're using, people in your

00:03:04.679 --> 00:03:05.679
team.

00:03:05.679 --> 00:03:10.559
So lots of people are actually teachers or teaching, so I hope you get something out

00:03:10.559 --> 00:03:11.960
of this talk.

00:03:11.960 --> 00:03:14.559
First, mandatory audience participation.

00:03:14.559 --> 00:03:16.279
Who knows who said this?

00:03:16.279 --> 00:03:17.399
Everyone should learn programming.

00:03:17.399 --> 00:03:21.399
Any guesses from the audience?

00:03:21.399 --> 00:03:25.399
Steve Jobs?

00:03:25.399 --> 00:03:26.399
Barack Obama?

00:03:26.399 --> 00:03:29.039
Well, maybe.

00:03:29.039 --> 00:03:32.240
I think it's like every programmer ever.

00:03:32.240 --> 00:03:35.839
You are all guilty of this, because we love programming.

00:03:35.839 --> 00:03:39.800
We're like, oh, programming is the best, so everyone should learn programming.

00:03:39.800 --> 00:03:47.000
But it's fun, but it also opens up a super interesting question, because what is programming?

00:03:47.000 --> 00:03:52.800
If I ask a bunch of people in this room what is programming, I might get 10, 20, 100 different

00:03:52.800 --> 00:03:53.960
answers.

00:03:53.960 --> 00:03:54.960
What is programming?

00:03:55.279 --> 00:04:00.360
It might be very well that what's programming to me isn't programming to you.

00:04:00.360 --> 00:04:05.839
And we programmers might not be the best people to answer this question.

00:04:05.839 --> 00:04:10.440
Maybe you've heard this story by David Foster Wallace that I absolutely love about three

00:04:10.440 --> 00:04:11.440
fish.

00:04:11.440 --> 00:04:15.880
So this big fish, he's swimming, and he runs into two tiny fish in the sea.

00:04:15.880 --> 00:04:19.880
And the big fish says, hey, folks, how's the water?

00:04:19.880 --> 00:04:24.640
And the tiny fish say, what's water?

00:04:24.640 --> 00:04:28.040
We programmers, we are those tiny fish.

00:04:28.040 --> 00:04:34.679
We are so much swimming in the sea of programming that it gets really, really hard for us to

00:04:34.679 --> 00:04:40.399
see we're in that sea, to understand that we are actually influenced by this water of

00:04:40.399 --> 00:04:42.440
programming, as I call it.

00:04:42.440 --> 00:04:44.239
So how did I came to think about this?

00:04:44.239 --> 00:04:48.959
It wasn't that one sunny morning I woke up and I thought, oh, today I'm going to ponder

00:04:48.959 --> 00:04:51.119
what programming actually is.

00:04:51.119 --> 00:04:55.239
There was a sort of long backstory to this involving my PhD work.

00:04:55.239 --> 00:05:02.160
So let's go back to the year 2008, when I moved from Eindhoven, where I did my master's

00:05:02.160 --> 00:05:06.839
and bachelor's degree, to Delft, where I started a PhD in software engineering.

00:05:06.839 --> 00:05:08.920
This is the tier Delft.

00:05:08.920 --> 00:05:15.839
And my research question for my PhD was to make a DSL, a domain-specific language for

00:05:15.839 --> 00:05:17.119
finance.

00:05:17.119 --> 00:05:19.200
That was actually my research goal.

00:05:19.279 --> 00:05:23.660
So my supervisor and me, we envisioned something like this, a programming language in which

00:05:23.660 --> 00:05:29.559
people in finance, bankers, insurers, people like that, could express their business logic

00:05:29.559 --> 00:05:33.440
such that they didn't need programmers for everything, because there aren't a lot of

00:05:33.440 --> 00:05:34.440
programmers.

00:05:34.440 --> 00:05:38.239
And also it's very empowering, of course, for people that have no full programming degree

00:05:38.239 --> 00:05:42.079
or experience to be able to make some small things for their own needs.

00:05:42.079 --> 00:05:47.079
So this is what we envisioned to work on for four years in my PhD.

00:05:47.079 --> 00:05:51.320
And the first thing that I did when I started is I did an internship at a Dutch insurance

00:05:51.320 --> 00:05:52.320
company.

00:05:52.320 --> 00:05:57.079
I went there just to look around and to see, what are people actually doing in industry?

00:05:57.079 --> 00:06:01.600
Because in my bachelor's and master's degree, I hadn't got lots of experience of how stuff

00:06:01.600 --> 00:06:03.119
actually works.

00:06:03.119 --> 00:06:06.200
And my mental model of the world was sort of this.

00:06:06.200 --> 00:06:10.799
I'm not sure if they still teach this in universities, but when I graduated, this was how I saw the

00:06:10.799 --> 00:06:11.799
world.

00:06:11.799 --> 00:06:13.959
There are users.

00:06:13.959 --> 00:06:15.779
And there are also programmers.

00:06:15.779 --> 00:06:19.540
They are entirely different species with a wall between them.

00:06:19.540 --> 00:06:22.220
They have nothing to do with each other.

00:06:22.220 --> 00:06:25.899
Maybe sometimes they converse a little bit through the wall, but in general, they're

00:06:25.899 --> 00:06:27.779
entirely different people.

00:06:27.779 --> 00:06:30.179
And the programmers program, and the users use.

00:06:30.179 --> 00:06:34.859
This was my view of the world, fresh coming out of school, into this internship in this

00:06:34.859 --> 00:06:36.100
insurance company.

00:06:36.100 --> 00:06:39.899
So I was going to look and see, what are the programmers doing, and what are the users

00:06:39.899 --> 00:06:40.899
doing?

00:06:40.899 --> 00:06:44.600
Well, turned out, it was more like this.

00:06:44.600 --> 00:06:47.119
Everyone in the company was programming, all of them.

00:06:47.119 --> 00:06:51.239
The programmers were programming, but also the other non-programmers, people that didn't

00:06:51.239 --> 00:06:57.359
have programming as a part of their job title or former role, they were also programming.

00:06:57.359 --> 00:07:01.799
But they weren't programming like this in a traditional programming language, of course.

00:07:01.799 --> 00:07:05.040
They were programming in spreadsheets.

00:07:05.040 --> 00:07:08.899
This whole insurance company was ran on spreadsheets.

00:07:08.899 --> 00:07:13.320
They had risk models of all their assets in all different types of countries.

00:07:13.320 --> 00:07:14.320
Where are we investing?

00:07:15.040 --> 00:07:23.160
It was all ran inside spreadsheets, made by a non-programmer, an end-user programmer.

00:07:23.160 --> 00:07:24.160
Wow!

00:07:24.160 --> 00:07:30.040
That is weird, because they told me in school all those years that normal people, the non-programmers,

00:07:30.040 --> 00:07:34.720
they needed our programming help to make things, because they could only write things like

00:07:34.720 --> 00:07:36.000
requirements and stuff.

00:07:36.000 --> 00:07:37.000
They couldn't do programming.

00:07:37.000 --> 00:07:38.920
So I was like, wow!

00:07:38.920 --> 00:07:44.359
So I went back to my supervisor, I said, friends, they don't need a domain-specific language

00:07:44.359 --> 00:07:45.359
in finance.

00:07:45.359 --> 00:07:50.600
They have a domain-specific language in finance, and it's Excel.

00:07:50.600 --> 00:07:58.640
Whatever we're going to work on in this four-year PhD project is never going to be as good as

00:07:58.640 --> 00:08:00.440
spreadsheets.

00:08:00.440 --> 00:08:02.600
It's never going to happen.

00:08:02.600 --> 00:08:07.959
Spreadsheets, and I really say this without any irony, spreadsheets are the best programming

00:08:08.000 --> 00:08:13.160
system that has ever existed in the history of mankind.

00:08:13.160 --> 00:08:19.559
Spreadsheets are such a good programming system that people can program without knowing their

00:08:19.559 --> 00:08:20.559
programming.

00:08:20.559 --> 00:08:24.359
Let that sink in for a bit.

00:08:24.359 --> 00:08:27.600
Imagine this happening for another programming language.

00:08:27.600 --> 00:08:31.440
Imagine accidentally doing Java.

00:08:32.440 --> 00:08:36.159
Like, hey, I installed Eclipse on this laptop.

00:08:36.159 --> 00:08:40.440
It was super easy to do on Windows, and then I opened it up, and I immediately knew what

00:08:40.440 --> 00:08:46.359
to do, and now I build a risk management model for our company.

00:08:46.359 --> 00:08:53.919
See how unlikely that is with Java, or C Sharp, or probably even R?

00:08:53.919 --> 00:08:56.119
Excel is such a good programming model.

00:08:56.119 --> 00:08:59.960
People just know what to do, and they can start doing it immediately, and they can add

00:08:59.960 --> 00:09:05.280
formulas and pivot tables and VBA, but initially, it's just so intuitive.

00:09:05.280 --> 00:09:11.359
This model where you get live feedback from a spreadsheet, it's just a programming language.

00:09:11.359 --> 00:09:16.080
So that became the motto of my PhD dissertation.

00:09:16.080 --> 00:09:17.080
Spreadsheets are code.

00:09:17.080 --> 00:09:22.159
We should take spreadsheets seriously as a programming paradigm, because people are running

00:09:22.159 --> 00:09:27.719
companies with it, and people are very, very successful in building stuff with it.

00:09:27.760 --> 00:09:31.080
But spreadsheets are not just codes.

00:09:31.080 --> 00:09:34.520
They're actually functional programming.

00:09:34.520 --> 00:09:38.599
As I showed in the MongNet talk that Daniel was talking about, a formula in a spreadsheet

00:09:38.599 --> 00:09:41.599
is guaranteed to be side effect free.

00:09:41.599 --> 00:09:46.840
A formula just takes input from other cells, and then calculates the results based upon

00:09:46.840 --> 00:09:48.280
those cells.

00:09:48.280 --> 00:09:50.599
So it never has side effects.

00:09:50.599 --> 00:09:53.799
It's pure functional programming.

00:09:53.799 --> 00:09:56.039
Spreadsheets are also reactive programming.

00:09:56.080 --> 00:09:59.640
The spreadsheet model works in such a way that if you update a cell, only the cells

00:09:59.640 --> 00:10:04.799
that depend on that cell will be updated, and not a full recalculation of the spreadsheet

00:10:04.799 --> 00:10:06.080
is needed.

00:10:06.080 --> 00:10:13.440
So it's pure functional reactive programming, and still, 750 million people are able to

00:10:13.440 --> 00:10:15.400
use it in an easy way.

00:10:15.400 --> 00:10:17.640
Like, eat that, Haskell!

00:10:17.640 --> 00:10:19.880
Like, wow!

00:10:19.880 --> 00:10:25.880
So this became the motto of my PhD dissertation, and I wrote a bunch of papers on it.

00:10:26.719 --> 00:10:27.719
It was super cool.

00:10:27.719 --> 00:10:32.520
We did smell detection for spreadsheets, refactoring for spreadsheets, we did clone detection for

00:10:32.520 --> 00:10:33.520
spreadsheets.

00:10:33.520 --> 00:10:37.400
All those things that you would normally do once you look at spreadsheets through the

00:10:37.400 --> 00:10:39.840
lens of it being a programming language.

00:10:39.840 --> 00:10:41.000
And then, hooray!

00:10:41.000 --> 00:10:42.000
I became a PhD.

00:10:42.000 --> 00:10:43.000
Awesome!

00:10:43.000 --> 00:10:45.679
I got my dissertation, and I wrote a book.

00:10:45.679 --> 00:10:47.679
Spreadsheets are code.

00:10:47.679 --> 00:10:48.679
Awesome!

00:10:48.679 --> 00:10:53.280
But you might wonder, where is this story about what is programming coming in?

00:10:53.280 --> 00:10:55.640
Why is this lady bragging about her thesis?

00:10:56.400 --> 00:10:57.719
Well, first of all, it was lots of work.

00:10:57.719 --> 00:11:05.440
But also, there's a point to this story, because this part of the story where the things actually

00:11:05.440 --> 00:11:10.719
happened, it's true, they're facts, but they're only that, they're only facts.

00:11:10.719 --> 00:11:16.799
But there's also a story of the heart, of what was I feeling when I was doing all these

00:11:16.799 --> 00:11:17.840
things?

00:11:17.840 --> 00:11:22.159
And that's where the programming stuff, the what-is-programming stuff comes in.

00:11:22.159 --> 00:11:25.760
When I did this talk previously, someone said, it looks like Felina is doing therapy

00:11:25.760 --> 00:11:27.359
with an audience.

00:11:27.359 --> 00:11:28.359
That's true.

00:11:28.359 --> 00:11:31.479
Let's talk about feelings for a while, because feelings actually matter a lot.

00:11:31.479 --> 00:11:36.880
So this is me, super cool, going to programming conferences, because I really like speaking.

00:11:36.880 --> 00:11:41.359
So even early in my PhD, I submitted talks to programming conferences, because I thought,

00:11:41.359 --> 00:11:46.280
oh, I have a cool story, and I just like being on stage, so why not submit some talks around

00:11:46.280 --> 00:11:47.359
spreadsheets are code?

00:11:47.359 --> 00:11:51.359
So going to conferences and doing talks like this.

00:11:51.559 --> 00:11:54.559
And the people there are like, it's not real programming.

00:11:54.559 --> 00:12:01.280
But I was like, wait, wait, wait, wait, wait, wait.

00:12:01.280 --> 00:12:02.280
Hear me out.

00:12:02.280 --> 00:12:07.799
But there, functional programming and reactive programming, and look, I build a monad.

00:12:07.799 --> 00:12:14.840
I even, to make my point, build a Turing machine in spreadsheets, formal as only to show that

00:12:14.840 --> 00:12:15.840
it's Turing-complete.

00:12:15.840 --> 00:12:18.840
I mean, what else can I do to convince them?

00:12:18.840 --> 00:12:19.840
I have monads.

00:12:19.840 --> 00:12:22.359
So I have Turing-completeness.

00:12:22.359 --> 00:12:24.919
It didn't matter.

00:12:24.919 --> 00:12:28.640
They were still like, it's not real programming.

00:12:28.640 --> 00:12:36.119
And that went on for a while, and a while, and a while.

00:12:36.119 --> 00:12:40.840
And I mean, I'm laughing now, but at that point, I was really sort of sad.

00:12:40.840 --> 00:12:43.559
Who in the audience has a PhD or is working on one?

00:12:43.559 --> 00:12:45.400
Yeah, a bunch.

00:12:45.400 --> 00:12:49.799
So you and your topic become this one thing.

00:12:49.799 --> 00:12:56.679
And if people say your topic is not real or not worthwhile or anything, then it really

00:12:56.679 --> 00:12:58.400
hurts.

00:12:58.400 --> 00:13:04.479
And I really got, I don't want to say depressed, because I'm not qualified to diagnose myself,

00:13:04.479 --> 00:13:07.840
but at least I was really, really sad.

00:13:07.840 --> 00:13:13.080
Because there was such a big difference between how important I thought the stuff was that

00:13:13.080 --> 00:13:19.960
I was working on and how other people viewed my topic as not real programming.

00:13:19.960 --> 00:13:25.359
That was definitely one of the biggest reasons that I'm not doing spreadsheet research anymore.

00:13:25.359 --> 00:13:31.239
I was just sick of this behavior of people telling me my work wasn't real.

00:13:31.239 --> 00:13:36.440
And at this point, I really thought, this is how adults treat each other.

00:13:36.440 --> 00:13:40.599
I thought, well, you know, apparently, if you're an adult, if you're in an adult professional

00:13:40.599 --> 00:13:43.960
community, people just be shit to each other.

00:13:43.960 --> 00:13:47.719
I just have to maybe toughen up, I don't know, because apparently it is like this.

00:13:47.719 --> 00:13:54.239
It was only until way later, like, let's go to 2015, when I realized that people can be

00:13:54.239 --> 00:13:56.320
nice to each other.

00:13:56.320 --> 00:13:57.440
Sort of sad.

00:13:57.440 --> 00:14:01.359
So I joined a running club.

00:14:01.359 --> 00:14:02.359
Super cool.

00:14:02.359 --> 00:14:03.359
So I joined a running club.

00:14:03.359 --> 00:14:04.359
And I'm not a great runner.

00:14:04.359 --> 00:14:07.159
Like, my fastest half marathon is two hours and 10 minutes.

00:14:07.159 --> 00:14:11.599
I have friends in the running club that do a half marathon in like one hour five.

00:14:11.599 --> 00:14:16.000
So they're literally twice as quick as I am.

00:14:16.000 --> 00:14:22.000
But no one in the running community will ever say stuff like, I'm not a real runner.

00:14:22.000 --> 00:14:23.000
Never.

00:14:23.000 --> 00:14:27.159
Who in the audience is a runner?

00:14:27.159 --> 00:14:28.159
So we're the worst.

00:14:28.159 --> 00:14:31.559
You know, runners, we want to make everyone runners.

00:14:31.559 --> 00:14:35.799
We're like Jehovah's Witnesses, like, ding dong, have you heard the happy news about

00:14:35.799 --> 00:14:36.799
running?

00:14:37.440 --> 00:14:38.440
I'll catch you running to the bus.

00:14:38.440 --> 00:14:39.440
I'll be like, oh, do you like running?

00:14:39.440 --> 00:14:40.440
Do you want to go on a race together?

00:14:40.440 --> 00:14:41.440
What's your personal record?

00:14:41.440 --> 00:14:42.440
We're the worst.

00:14:42.440 --> 00:14:46.440
I mean, we're the best.

00:14:46.440 --> 00:14:50.200
No one will ever say stuff like, you're not a real runner.

00:14:50.200 --> 00:14:55.719
They don't say shit like, oh, you have Adidas shoes?

00:14:55.719 --> 00:15:01.280
But they have security vulnerabilities.

00:15:01.280 --> 00:15:04.119
No one is like that.

00:15:04.119 --> 00:15:06.280
Everyone is super nice to each other.

00:15:06.280 --> 00:15:09.359
I'm like, as I said, I'm the slowest, and people root for me.

00:15:09.359 --> 00:15:13.280
They never say, like, give up on this because you're not a real runner.

00:15:13.280 --> 00:15:17.840
We've been in a pub for one hour, no one.

00:15:17.840 --> 00:15:25.000
But compare this to my experience in programming.

00:15:25.000 --> 00:15:28.799
Only later I realized that it doesn't have to be like this.

00:15:28.799 --> 00:15:30.159
And it's not just running.

00:15:30.159 --> 00:15:31.440
I'm also a knitter.

00:15:31.440 --> 00:15:33.320
I really love knitting.

00:15:33.320 --> 00:15:35.280
And I knitted a lot when I was a teenager.

00:15:35.280 --> 00:15:37.479
But then I went to university, you know, life happens.

00:15:37.479 --> 00:15:39.719
So I sort of gave up on knitting.

00:15:39.719 --> 00:15:41.799
And then in 2016, I came back to knitting.

00:15:41.799 --> 00:15:45.840
And I went to a knitting meetup, which is a thing, it's super nice.

00:15:45.840 --> 00:15:52.400
So I went there with my old-fashioned straight needles that you got as a hand-you-down from

00:15:52.400 --> 00:15:56.159
your mother, from your grandparents, straight needles.

00:15:56.159 --> 00:15:57.880
These apparently are out of fashion.

00:15:57.880 --> 00:15:59.539
People now use circular needles.

00:15:59.539 --> 00:16:00.539
I didn't know this.

00:16:00.539 --> 00:16:02.159
I'm like, come on to this meetup.

00:16:02.159 --> 00:16:03.559
Everyone has different needles but me.

00:16:03.880 --> 00:16:06.719
I'm like, oh, shit, this is going to be not real knitting.

00:16:09.440 --> 00:16:13.840
They're going to be mean to me for using this not real skill.

00:16:13.840 --> 00:16:14.799
But they weren't.

00:16:14.799 --> 00:16:16.159
They were super nice.

00:16:16.159 --> 00:16:18.119
They said, oh, you know, we all use those needles.

00:16:18.119 --> 00:16:20.559
But let us show you how you do this.

00:16:20.559 --> 00:16:26.799
And this is what the benefits are, but in a super nice way, not in a demeaning way.

00:16:26.799 --> 00:16:30.599
And that made me look back at my experience in programming.

00:16:30.599 --> 00:16:35.960
And I was like, why are they so mean?

00:16:35.960 --> 00:16:37.840
And I don't have an answer for you.

00:16:37.840 --> 00:16:41.239
It's maybe something to ponder on later, like, why is programming like that?

00:16:41.239 --> 00:16:42.520
I don't know.

00:16:42.520 --> 00:16:44.919
But I didn't know all of that stuff in 2012.

00:16:44.919 --> 00:16:47.200
So let's go back to 2012.

00:16:47.200 --> 00:16:50.159
I'm like, super sad.

00:16:50.159 --> 00:16:52.080
I really started hating spreadsheets.

00:16:52.080 --> 00:16:56.320
But I had just accepted a position at Delft University as an assistant professor.

00:16:56.320 --> 00:16:58.960
And in my job interview, blatantly lied that I

00:16:58.960 --> 00:17:00.799
was super excited about spreadsheets.

00:17:00.799 --> 00:17:03.280
And then for five years, I was going to work on it.

00:17:03.280 --> 00:17:04.719
And also, I got a grant proposal.

00:17:04.719 --> 00:17:09.599
So I had two PhD students and a postdoc ready to work on spreadsheets.

00:17:09.599 --> 00:17:12.839
But I wasn't feeling it, so not great.

00:17:12.839 --> 00:17:15.359
Luckily, what really saved my happiness there

00:17:15.359 --> 00:17:19.560
was I ran into a bunch of kids in a local community center in Rotterdam

00:17:19.560 --> 00:17:20.599
where I live.

00:17:20.599 --> 00:17:23.920
And they needed a programming teacher on Saturdays.

00:17:23.920 --> 00:17:26.800
So I was like, OK, I can do that.

00:17:26.800 --> 00:17:29.119
Let me teach programming on Saturdays.

00:17:29.119 --> 00:17:33.880
Then at least I have the feeling I'm doing something useful one day a week.

00:17:33.880 --> 00:17:35.839
And I'll figure out work stuff later.

00:17:35.839 --> 00:17:38.880
But at least I'll be doing something useful.

00:17:38.880 --> 00:17:41.640
So I picked up that position at that school.

00:17:41.640 --> 00:17:43.439
I actually still do that every Saturday.

00:17:43.439 --> 00:17:46.479
And I'm flying back after this talk, so I'm in time to teach tomorrow.

00:17:49.280 --> 00:17:51.119
And it was heartwarming.

00:17:51.119 --> 00:17:56.760
It was really nice to see kids coming in on Saturday to learn programming.

00:17:56.760 --> 00:18:01.040
But I didn't know anything about teaching.

00:18:01.040 --> 00:18:02.959
I had no clue about teaching.

00:18:02.959 --> 00:18:08.719
Obviously, I taught a little bit at university, but this was different.

00:18:08.719 --> 00:18:10.479
I just didn't know how to approach it.

00:18:10.479 --> 00:18:11.560
I had no plan.

00:18:11.560 --> 00:18:13.199
And I also wasn't considering a plan.

00:18:13.199 --> 00:18:17.160
I just thought, hmm, let's go there and we'll see what happens.

00:18:17.160 --> 00:18:20.640
And I think what happened in my brain, not consciously but subconsciously,

00:18:20.640 --> 00:18:25.079
I started thinking about how I was learning when I was their age.

00:18:25.079 --> 00:18:29.119
So this is me, age 10, behind the computer.

00:18:29.119 --> 00:18:29.880
We had a computer.

00:18:29.880 --> 00:18:34.680
And I had this book of basic listings that I got from the library.

00:18:34.680 --> 00:18:38.520
And I just typed up the basic listings in my computer for hours.

00:18:38.520 --> 00:18:41.319
And it didn't work because I had syntax errors.

00:18:41.319 --> 00:18:42.599
And then I fixed all of those.

00:18:42.599 --> 00:18:45.199
And it still didn't work because I made indentation errors

00:18:45.199 --> 00:18:47.280
and whatever type of mistakes.

00:18:47.280 --> 00:18:48.599
But then in a while, it worked.

00:18:48.599 --> 00:18:50.160
And I had a game in BASIC.

00:18:50.160 --> 00:18:52.880
And that's sort of how I learned programming.

00:18:52.880 --> 00:18:56.400
And that's what I was thinking of in that Saturday club, that experience

00:18:56.400 --> 00:19:01.280
just giving kids syntax books, basically, and having them copy it.

00:19:01.280 --> 00:19:02.640
And then they will learn.

00:19:02.640 --> 00:19:07.479
And notice the absence of a teacher or an adult in this story.

00:19:07.479 --> 00:19:11.880
No one was teaching me programming, apart from maybe the book.

00:19:11.880 --> 00:19:14.040
But there wasn't another person.

00:19:14.040 --> 00:19:17.520
So this was my experience learning programming

00:19:17.520 --> 00:19:20.040
without an adult or a teacher present.

00:19:20.119 --> 00:19:20.959
And it's not just me.

00:19:20.959 --> 00:19:27.040
Many people of my generation that grew up in the 80s learned programming alone,

00:19:27.040 --> 00:19:31.079
learned programming by themselves, taught themselves programming.

00:19:31.079 --> 00:19:35.760
A recent survey on Stack Overflow among hundreds of thousands of developers

00:19:35.760 --> 00:19:40.920
stated that 80% of developers taught themselves programming.

00:19:40.920 --> 00:19:44.640
So this idea of how to teach programming,

00:19:44.640 --> 00:19:46.599
we don't know how to teach programming.

00:19:46.599 --> 00:19:51.719
As a community, we don't have a shared collective memory

00:19:51.719 --> 00:19:55.000
of what a programming lesson looks like other

00:19:55.000 --> 00:20:01.719
than us being alone with a Commodore 64 or something like that.

00:20:01.719 --> 00:20:04.959
And that does something to us as a community,

00:20:04.959 --> 00:20:08.599
that we lack this experience of being in a programming class

00:20:08.599 --> 00:20:10.800
until we're 18 in university.

00:20:10.800 --> 00:20:15.239
And of course, then you are already shaped a bit as a person.

00:20:15.239 --> 00:20:18.959
So this led to this idea with me, but also with other people,

00:20:18.959 --> 00:20:21.119
just let kids explore the programming language.

00:20:21.119 --> 00:20:23.160
Just give them the basic listings.

00:20:23.160 --> 00:20:25.199
Well, it's maybe Scratch now or Python.

00:20:25.199 --> 00:20:26.400
But just give it to them.

00:20:26.400 --> 00:20:27.119
And they'll explore.

00:20:27.119 --> 00:20:28.199
And they'll figure it out.

00:20:28.199 --> 00:20:31.520
And they'll pick it up naturally.

00:20:31.520 --> 00:20:36.119
And as I said, it's really part of our collective memory

00:20:36.119 --> 00:20:37.479
to learn in such a way.

00:20:37.479 --> 00:20:42.000
And you can also see that if you look at programming books for children.

00:20:42.000 --> 00:20:44.119
So I bought some books, just went to the bookshop,

00:20:44.719 --> 00:20:48.280
programming for kids books, and brought them to the Saturday Club.

00:20:48.280 --> 00:20:51.800
But once you start looking on the things that are in there,

00:20:51.800 --> 00:20:53.319
it's sort of weird.

00:20:53.319 --> 00:20:56.479
So it's in Dutch, but I translated it underneath.

00:20:56.479 --> 00:21:01.400
So this says, the best part of programming is finding mistakes.

00:21:04.640 --> 00:21:07.359
Yeah, it's funny, but it's also interesting.

00:21:07.359 --> 00:21:10.079
So notice what it doesn't say.

00:21:10.079 --> 00:21:12.280
It doesn't say the best part of programming

00:21:12.280 --> 00:21:15.800
is making something, creative expression.

00:21:15.800 --> 00:21:18.199
And it doesn't say the best part of programming

00:21:18.199 --> 00:21:21.119
is being able to find a well-paid job, which

00:21:21.119 --> 00:21:22.880
actually matters to many people.

00:21:22.880 --> 00:21:24.640
It's a good reason to go into programming.

00:21:24.640 --> 00:21:26.599
I mean, I like having a house.

00:21:26.599 --> 00:21:29.040
So that's a good reason.

00:21:29.040 --> 00:21:33.959
It's interesting that one part of programming, the puzzly part,

00:21:33.959 --> 00:21:38.280
is really very stressed as the best part.

00:21:38.599 --> 00:21:41.199
In a similar vein, it says programmers only

00:21:41.199 --> 00:21:43.520
learn from making mistakes.

00:21:43.520 --> 00:21:46.680
And there's some ambiguity also in the Dutch version

00:21:46.680 --> 00:21:49.959
where it is, can you only learn from mistakes?

00:21:49.959 --> 00:21:53.199
Or if a mistake happens, the only thing you can do

00:21:53.199 --> 00:21:54.400
is learn from it.

00:21:54.400 --> 00:21:56.599
But why?

00:21:56.599 --> 00:21:58.640
Why would I only learn from making mistakes?

00:21:58.640 --> 00:22:00.800
Why wouldn't I learn from being told

00:22:00.800 --> 00:22:04.520
how to do it in a proper way?

00:22:04.560 --> 00:22:06.760
That seems to be so much more efficient.

00:22:10.199 --> 00:22:13.560
This is also nice.

00:22:13.560 --> 00:22:15.000
And these are books.

00:22:15.000 --> 00:22:17.680
They're geared towards eight, nine-year-olds.

00:22:17.680 --> 00:22:18.800
So look at me.

00:22:18.800 --> 00:22:22.239
I'm an eight, nine-year-old in a bookshop picking up a book.

00:22:22.239 --> 00:22:25.599
Maybe I want to do horseback riding, pictures of horses,

00:22:25.599 --> 00:22:26.400
petting them.

00:22:26.400 --> 00:22:27.199
Oh, they're so cute.

00:22:27.199 --> 00:22:28.199
They're like unicorns.

00:22:28.199 --> 00:22:29.239
Picking up another book.

00:22:29.239 --> 00:22:30.920
Maybe I'm interested in something else.

00:22:30.920 --> 00:22:31.599
Programming.

00:22:31.599 --> 00:22:32.760
You will fail.

00:22:32.760 --> 00:22:34.479
And all of them are like, never mind.

00:22:37.479 --> 00:22:39.239
I mean, it's sort of nice because at least

00:22:39.239 --> 00:22:40.800
the people they scare away don't have

00:22:40.800 --> 00:22:43.520
to go through the whole not real programming, right?

00:22:43.520 --> 00:22:45.239
I mean, maybe that's better in the end.

00:22:45.239 --> 00:22:47.880
But this is interesting.

00:22:47.880 --> 00:22:51.000
Why do we tell this to kids?

00:22:51.000 --> 00:22:52.199
I don't know.

00:22:52.199 --> 00:22:55.680
Because maybe we're not a great community.

00:22:55.680 --> 00:23:00.479
Never be afraid to mess around, try out, and experiment.

00:23:02.959 --> 00:23:04.839
It doesn't really mean anything.

00:23:04.839 --> 00:23:07.719
But the next part of this is more interesting.

00:23:07.719 --> 00:23:12.479
It says, break the rules.

00:23:12.479 --> 00:23:17.520
If you're programming, it is important to break the rules.

00:23:17.520 --> 00:23:19.520
OK, I guess.

00:23:19.520 --> 00:23:21.959
But this is a book about Python.

00:23:21.959 --> 00:23:24.319
So let's go further a few pages.

00:23:24.319 --> 00:23:26.199
Same book.

00:23:26.199 --> 00:23:27.920
The colon goes there.

00:23:27.920 --> 00:23:29.119
The space goes there.

00:23:29.119 --> 00:23:31.719
The space needs to be in the right place.

00:23:31.719 --> 00:23:33.880
Otherwise, Python will be very angry.

00:23:33.880 --> 00:23:36.280
And it will shout syntax error at you.

00:23:36.280 --> 00:23:37.760
And you have no clue what it means.

00:23:37.760 --> 00:23:40.400
And the file stuff, the colon goes there.

00:23:40.400 --> 00:23:41.439
And the quote goes there.

00:23:41.439 --> 00:23:43.119
And the rectangular brackets go there.

00:23:43.119 --> 00:23:44.400
But also, break the rules.

00:23:49.079 --> 00:23:52.439
Get your shit together, programming.

00:23:52.439 --> 00:24:00.280
But same code statement, the most important thing, it's fun.

00:24:00.280 --> 00:24:01.839
So it will be frustrating.

00:24:01.839 --> 00:24:04.839
You have to break the rules, but also not break the rules

00:24:04.839 --> 00:24:06.040
because of the syntax.

00:24:06.040 --> 00:24:07.800
And if you're not having fun, you're

00:24:07.800 --> 00:24:11.199
doing it wrong because the most important thing, people,

00:24:11.199 --> 00:24:12.319
is you should have fun.

00:24:15.280 --> 00:24:19.959
So you see, this culture of trying out, exploring,

00:24:19.959 --> 00:24:23.359
is very much in everything we are.

00:24:23.359 --> 00:24:25.920
And part of it, that is our experience.

00:24:25.920 --> 00:24:28.640
Part of that is our culture.

00:24:28.640 --> 00:24:30.400
So that's what I did as well.

00:24:30.400 --> 00:24:31.920
I bought those books.

00:24:31.920 --> 00:24:33.520
I put them in the group.

00:24:33.520 --> 00:24:36.239
And I just had, let kids explore.

00:24:36.239 --> 00:24:37.719
And I did focus on concepts.

00:24:37.719 --> 00:24:41.920
So I said things like, a loop is an important concept

00:24:41.920 --> 00:24:42.839
that you need to know.

00:24:42.839 --> 00:24:45.680
It is about repetition, stuff like that.

00:24:45.680 --> 00:24:48.839
But I didn't really thought it really, really matters

00:24:48.839 --> 00:24:51.359
where the colon goes in Python.

00:24:51.359 --> 00:24:53.119
I didn't really talk about it because I

00:24:53.119 --> 00:24:55.280
was in this mindset of, oh, exploring.

00:24:55.280 --> 00:24:56.599
Oh, they'll figure it out.

00:24:56.599 --> 00:24:57.880
They'll get an error message.

00:24:57.880 --> 00:25:00.719
And the only thing they can do is learn from that.

00:25:00.719 --> 00:25:02.479
That was my thinking.

00:25:02.479 --> 00:25:07.400
And surprisingly, it didn't really go amazing.

00:25:07.400 --> 00:25:09.640
So I saw kids making some progress.

00:25:09.640 --> 00:25:12.959
But then eventually, they got really, really frustrated.

00:25:12.959 --> 00:25:14.959
And the nice thing about teaching eight-year-olds

00:25:14.959 --> 00:25:19.239
versus university students is that if an eight-year-old is

00:25:19.239 --> 00:25:20.719
confused, they will tell you.

00:25:20.719 --> 00:25:24.439
They will take this book and throw it on the table

00:25:24.439 --> 00:25:26.760
and say, I hate this.

00:25:26.760 --> 00:25:29.000
But it's a good experience as a teacher

00:25:29.000 --> 00:25:34.079
because when students come into university,

00:25:34.079 --> 00:25:36.680
they get scared about saying they don't understand things.

00:25:36.680 --> 00:25:38.839
So I mean, it's clear that if you give a lecture

00:25:38.839 --> 00:25:40.520
to a big lecture hall with 18-year-olds,

00:25:40.520 --> 00:25:41.760
some of them will not get it.

00:25:41.760 --> 00:25:44.920
But they won't come up to you and hit you with a book.

00:25:44.920 --> 00:25:48.239
They'll go home and be in their dorm

00:25:48.239 --> 00:25:50.119
and cry and be frustrated or maybe drop out

00:25:50.119 --> 00:25:51.359
because they don't understand.

00:25:51.359 --> 00:25:53.719
So the type of feedback you get from that group

00:25:53.719 --> 00:25:56.520
is very different from the type of feedback, good feedback,

00:25:57.280 --> 00:25:59.239
you get from younger kids.

00:25:59.239 --> 00:26:02.640
So then I started to look into research that has been done

00:26:02.640 --> 00:26:05.319
because I thought, wow, people must have tried this

00:26:05.319 --> 00:26:06.839
in research, and they did.

00:26:06.839 --> 00:26:09.479
There's actually this nice paper by Scafidi and Chambers

00:26:09.479 --> 00:26:13.040
that looked at skill progressions in Scratch users.

00:26:13.040 --> 00:26:15.439
So Scratch is a visual programming language

00:26:15.439 --> 00:26:17.439
very much aimed at young children.

00:26:17.439 --> 00:26:21.000
And they sampled children throughout a number of projects

00:26:21.000 --> 00:26:23.719
and they looked at, okay, what are the kids doing?

00:26:23.719 --> 00:26:27.000
So firstly, they found very, very high dropout.

00:26:27.000 --> 00:26:30.319
So kids register, make a project, and then they quit.

00:26:30.319 --> 00:26:32.599
That doesn't necessarily have to mean something, of course.

00:26:32.599 --> 00:26:35.719
Maybe they decided horseback riding was more for them

00:26:35.719 --> 00:26:37.640
or they immediately said, I want to go

00:26:37.640 --> 00:26:40.520
to a textual programming language like Python or Java.

00:26:40.520 --> 00:26:44.199
But they also found that kids initially made some progress

00:26:44.199 --> 00:26:47.359
and then their skill levels sort of flattened out.

00:26:47.359 --> 00:26:50.359
They didn't explore new blocks, new concepts.

00:26:50.359 --> 00:26:51.680
They had a few that worked for them

00:26:51.680 --> 00:26:54.119
and then sort of stuck with that.

00:26:54.119 --> 00:26:55.920
And they also didn't get more efficient.

00:26:55.920 --> 00:26:58.119
So you can imagine that once they know a few things,

00:26:58.119 --> 00:27:00.479
and at least they would be quicker at it,

00:27:00.479 --> 00:27:03.359
but also the efficiency sort of flattened out.

00:27:03.359 --> 00:27:05.160
And this very much looks like

00:27:05.160 --> 00:27:07.160
my Saturday classroom experience.

00:27:07.160 --> 00:27:08.839
Initially, kids made some progress,

00:27:08.839 --> 00:27:12.599
but then I couldn't get them to the next level

00:27:12.599 --> 00:27:14.280
and I didn't really know why.

00:27:14.280 --> 00:27:15.400
Well, I didn't know why

00:27:15.400 --> 00:27:17.359
because I didn't know anything about teaching,

00:27:17.359 --> 00:27:20.839
and that's why I was really, really bad at it.

00:27:20.839 --> 00:27:22.560
I don't know how this works in the US,

00:27:22.560 --> 00:27:23.800
but in the country I'm from,

00:27:23.800 --> 00:27:26.359
if you want to teach tiny humans in elementary school,

00:27:26.359 --> 00:27:29.599
you have to go to teacher school for four years.

00:27:29.599 --> 00:27:32.239
If you want to teach medium-sized humans in a high school,

00:27:32.239 --> 00:27:34.800
you have to go to school for five years.

00:27:34.800 --> 00:27:36.319
But if you want to teach at a university,

00:27:36.319 --> 00:27:39.880
you get your PhD in 12 Afternoons of Bloom's Taxonomy,

00:27:39.880 --> 00:27:41.199
and then you're good to go.

00:27:43.760 --> 00:27:45.400
This is really what happened to me.

00:27:45.400 --> 00:27:47.880
I got my PhD, I didn't know anything about teaching,

00:27:47.880 --> 00:27:50.079
and I got into a tenure track position.

00:27:50.719 --> 00:27:52.719
Teaching is super important to us,

00:27:52.719 --> 00:27:55.400
so you should know a lot about teaching.

00:27:55.400 --> 00:27:57.680
Here's 12 Afternoons of Bloom's.

00:27:58.839 --> 00:28:00.280
Good luck.

00:28:00.280 --> 00:28:03.920
So I really, despite being a professional educator

00:28:03.920 --> 00:28:06.560
in a well-ranked university,

00:28:06.560 --> 00:28:08.959
I really didn't know a lot about teaching.

00:28:08.959 --> 00:28:11.520
So I was like, I should fix this.

00:28:11.520 --> 00:28:15.780
I should know more about how we teach things

00:28:15.780 --> 00:28:17.880
because clearly this isn't going well

00:28:17.880 --> 00:28:20.680
and there's an opportunity for me to improve.

00:28:20.680 --> 00:28:21.920
So one of the things I did

00:28:21.920 --> 00:28:24.880
is I read the Oxford Handbook of Reading,

00:28:24.880 --> 00:28:26.800
which firstly stretches the definition

00:28:26.800 --> 00:28:28.040
of a handbook a little bit.

00:28:28.040 --> 00:28:30.760
It doesn't fit into my hands,

00:28:30.760 --> 00:28:32.560
but I have tiny hands, maybe.

00:28:32.560 --> 00:28:34.920
But it's really, really interesting.

00:28:34.920 --> 00:28:39.319
It's filled with all the things that humankind knows

00:28:39.319 --> 00:28:42.160
about how children or people read.

00:28:43.119 --> 00:28:45.079
So I was like, wow.

00:28:45.079 --> 00:28:47.800
We programming, we know nothing.

00:28:48.680 --> 00:28:50.880
People in linguistics research

00:28:50.880 --> 00:28:54.880
have figured out so many detailed things

00:28:54.880 --> 00:28:57.680
about how people read.

00:28:57.680 --> 00:29:00.239
Why aren't we doing that type of experiments?

00:29:00.239 --> 00:29:02.959
And one of the most interesting things

00:29:02.959 --> 00:29:05.859
I read in the Oxford Handbook of Reading

00:29:05.859 --> 00:29:10.859
is that how we pronounce things actually matters a lot.

00:29:11.199 --> 00:29:15.500
So this is already very vivid in young kids

00:29:15.500 --> 00:29:17.760
because one of the things you teach children

00:29:18.599 --> 00:29:20.719
is if they start reading, they sound out the letters.

00:29:20.719 --> 00:29:23.040
You're like, b, u, k, b.

00:29:23.040 --> 00:29:24.280
That's a way of reading.

00:29:24.280 --> 00:29:29.280
So memorizing letters and words very much goes through sound.

00:29:29.939 --> 00:29:34.000
We don't teach children silent reading initially.

00:29:34.000 --> 00:29:36.000
Actually, most kids only pick up silent reading

00:29:36.000 --> 00:29:37.640
if they're reading like a year.

00:29:37.640 --> 00:29:40.400
And they still sometimes, if people have kids this age,

00:29:40.400 --> 00:29:42.079
if they're six or seven, they're reading,

00:29:42.079 --> 00:29:43.540
you can still see them.

00:29:44.619 --> 00:29:47.239
They don't make a sound, but they still do that.

00:29:47.319 --> 00:29:51.400
And this actually also sound really matters for adults too.

00:29:51.400 --> 00:29:52.520
So I'm a scientist.

00:29:52.520 --> 00:29:54.520
Let's do an experiment.

00:29:54.520 --> 00:29:57.800
Mandatory audience participation.

00:29:57.800 --> 00:29:58.920
Tiny experiment.

00:29:58.920 --> 00:30:00.520
So this is what we're going to do.

00:30:00.520 --> 00:30:03.319
I'll show a sentence on the screen.

00:30:03.319 --> 00:30:05.839
Once you reach the end of the sentence,

00:30:05.839 --> 00:30:09.760
reading it silently in your brain, you raise your hand.

00:30:09.760 --> 00:30:11.439
So you get a sentence.

00:30:11.439 --> 00:30:13.920
If you're at the end, awesome.

00:30:13.920 --> 00:30:14.920
You raise your hand.

00:30:15.920 --> 00:30:18.359
There's a tiny caveat though.

00:30:18.359 --> 00:30:21.079
I won't show the sentence to you in full immediately.

00:30:21.079 --> 00:30:24.719
You get the first part of the sentence and then the second.

00:30:24.719 --> 00:30:26.619
And once you reach the end of the second,

00:30:26.619 --> 00:30:28.319
that's when you raise your hand.

00:30:28.319 --> 00:30:29.160
So let's try it.

00:30:35.400 --> 00:30:36.640
Perfect.

00:30:36.640 --> 00:30:38.760
Are you ready for the real experiment?

00:30:38.760 --> 00:30:39.599
Let's go.

00:30:45.920 --> 00:30:46.880
Here's another one.

00:30:53.319 --> 00:30:55.119
So I didn't do any statistics,

00:30:55.119 --> 00:30:59.359
but it seemed like the second took you a bit longer.

00:30:59.359 --> 00:31:02.520
And this has repeatedly been shown in lots of experiment

00:31:02.520 --> 00:31:06.119
that these type of sentences take people longer to perceive

00:31:06.119 --> 00:31:08.560
because clearly what's happening in your brain

00:31:08.560 --> 00:31:11.199
is you're reading, I have a tear,

00:31:11.199 --> 00:31:13.280
because you're thinking it will be in my eye.

00:31:13.319 --> 00:31:15.479
That's more likely sound.

00:31:15.479 --> 00:31:19.359
And then you see my pants and you have to go back,

00:31:19.359 --> 00:31:24.359
re-pronounce the sentence in your brain with tear,

00:31:24.520 --> 00:31:25.680
and then read the rest.

00:31:25.680 --> 00:31:27.000
You cannot not do that.

00:31:27.000 --> 00:31:32.000
You cannot in your brain hear, I have a tear,

00:31:32.000 --> 00:31:33.439
I have a tear in my pants.

00:31:33.439 --> 00:31:34.880
You see, I can't even do it.

00:31:36.119 --> 00:31:40.439
So this has shown consistently across proficient

00:31:40.439 --> 00:31:43.959
adult readers of English that to a certain extent,

00:31:43.959 --> 00:31:47.000
you always sound out stuff if you're reading.

00:31:47.000 --> 00:31:48.560
Actually, if you want to do speed reading,

00:31:48.560 --> 00:31:51.520
this is one of the first things you have to stop doing,

00:31:51.520 --> 00:31:53.239
but it's very, very hard.

00:31:53.239 --> 00:31:56.400
So how stuff sounds matters.

00:31:56.400 --> 00:31:59.180
But I wasn't necessarily impressed with this fact,

00:31:59.180 --> 00:32:01.800
even though it's a super cool fact.

00:32:01.800 --> 00:32:05.000
I was impressed with how well this was measured,

00:32:05.000 --> 00:32:08.760
that people set up an experiment to figure out

00:32:08.760 --> 00:32:10.520
how to read these type of sentences,

00:32:10.520 --> 00:32:13.339
and then they had repeated that over different cultures.

00:32:13.339 --> 00:32:17.079
My native language, Dutch, you wouldn't be able to do this

00:32:17.079 --> 00:32:21.680
because we don't have two letters that change sound,

00:32:21.680 --> 00:32:23.439
but we have other things that could confuse

00:32:23.439 --> 00:32:25.420
in terms of mispronunciation.

00:32:25.420 --> 00:32:27.680
So they have repeated this type of experiments,

00:32:27.680 --> 00:32:30.040
and they have real solid knowledge

00:32:30.040 --> 00:32:32.359
of how people read things.

00:32:32.359 --> 00:32:35.319
Like, we have no solid understanding

00:32:35.319 --> 00:32:37.979
of how people read source code, for example.

00:32:37.979 --> 00:32:42.500
No one has done similar experiments this solid

00:32:42.500 --> 00:32:45.020
and this repeated about reading source code.

00:32:45.020 --> 00:32:46.780
So I was like, wow!

00:32:48.219 --> 00:32:49.180
We know nothing.

00:32:49.180 --> 00:32:52.459
There's so much more to explore in programming.

00:32:52.459 --> 00:32:57.459
But the second thing I got from this book is we lack fight.

00:32:59.420 --> 00:33:03.540
In programming education, there's very much a monoculture,

00:33:03.540 --> 00:33:05.300
and of course, I don't mean a real fight,

00:33:05.339 --> 00:33:08.859
I mean some pedagogical diversity.

00:33:08.859 --> 00:33:12.140
In other fields like math and language,

00:33:12.140 --> 00:33:15.260
there are different streams, different beliefs

00:33:15.260 --> 00:33:20.260
from people of how to teach, and they argue about that,

00:33:21.420 --> 00:33:22.819
usually in a polite way,

00:33:22.819 --> 00:33:24.699
not in a you're-not-real-teaching way,

00:33:24.699 --> 00:33:27.140
but in a more solid way.

00:33:27.140 --> 00:33:29.099
And one of these debates, you might be aware of it,

00:33:29.099 --> 00:33:32.300
is called phonics versus whole language.

00:33:32.300 --> 00:33:35.260
These are two streams in reading education.

00:33:36.099 --> 00:33:39.140
So phonics is, like I just said, this sounding out.

00:33:39.140 --> 00:33:41.500
E, I, D, read.

00:33:41.500 --> 00:33:43.260
You start with the basic letters,

00:33:43.260 --> 00:33:45.260
and then words, and then sentences,

00:33:45.260 --> 00:33:48.479
and this is how you build up an understanding of children,

00:33:48.479 --> 00:33:49.819
of letters and words.

00:33:51.060 --> 00:33:52.939
You also have the whole language approach,

00:33:52.939 --> 00:33:55.339
and the whole language approach says,

00:33:55.339 --> 00:33:58.500
no, language is not about technical skills,

00:33:58.500 --> 00:34:00.459
language is about communication.

00:34:00.459 --> 00:34:03.099
So you shouldn't teach people individual letters

00:34:03.099 --> 00:34:04.300
because that technical skill

00:34:04.300 --> 00:34:06.739
is going to disengage them from reading.

00:34:06.739 --> 00:34:09.580
You should just give them sentences and context,

00:34:09.580 --> 00:34:12.500
and that's the better way to teach.

00:34:12.500 --> 00:34:14.659
There was also in the US in the 80s,

00:34:14.659 --> 00:34:15.780
you might be aware of this,

00:34:15.780 --> 00:34:19.100
something called the math wars,

00:34:19.100 --> 00:34:20.699
where in a similar vein,

00:34:20.699 --> 00:34:23.100
people were discussing how to teach math.

00:34:23.100 --> 00:34:25.459
So some people said, well, the way you teach math

00:34:25.459 --> 00:34:27.379
is you explain kids what to do,

00:34:27.379 --> 00:34:29.179
then they do it a whole bunch of times,

00:34:29.179 --> 00:34:30.659
and then they get it.

00:34:30.659 --> 00:34:32.020
On the other side of the aisle,

00:34:32.020 --> 00:34:37.020
you had, no, math is about finding the truth and beauty.

00:34:37.899 --> 00:34:40.580
So you shouldn't bore people with memorization,

00:34:40.580 --> 00:34:43.939
you should give them problems to explore.

00:34:43.939 --> 00:34:45.540
Exploration.

00:34:45.540 --> 00:34:50.540
Those are two sides of, two opinions of teaching.

00:34:50.780 --> 00:34:54.300
And we don't really have ever had that pedagogical debate

00:34:54.300 --> 00:34:56.939
where we're like, but wait, how do we even teach?

00:34:56.939 --> 00:34:59.899
This hasn't happened for programming.

00:34:59.899 --> 00:35:04.060
And probably that's because of this philosophy

00:35:04.060 --> 00:35:05.260
that we're not really aware of.

00:35:05.260 --> 00:35:07.340
So Alan Blackwell, a really interesting scientist

00:35:07.340 --> 00:35:12.340
from the UK, he says that technology is covert philosophy.

00:35:12.860 --> 00:35:15.379
It's a really interesting statement.

00:35:15.379 --> 00:35:16.659
It means something like,

00:35:16.659 --> 00:35:19.100
if someone has built a piece of technology,

00:35:19.100 --> 00:35:22.459
from that you can see what the people believe

00:35:22.459 --> 00:35:23.340
about the world.

00:35:23.340 --> 00:35:26.659
Like, people that have built something like Twitter,

00:35:26.659 --> 00:35:28.340
they might say it's neutral,

00:35:28.340 --> 00:35:32.020
but their beliefs that free speech is maybe more important

00:35:32.020 --> 00:35:33.860
than other things, you can see it

00:35:33.860 --> 00:35:36.179
from how they built that system.

00:35:36.179 --> 00:35:39.100
And in a similar way, I think education

00:35:39.100 --> 00:35:41.659
is also covert philosophy.

00:35:41.659 --> 00:35:44.620
You can learn a lot about the things people believe

00:35:44.620 --> 00:35:46.379
from the way they teach.

00:35:46.379 --> 00:35:48.580
There's a lot to learn about our culture

00:35:48.580 --> 00:35:50.060
from the way we teach.

00:35:50.060 --> 00:35:52.820
So there's not just the water of programming,

00:35:52.820 --> 00:35:56.340
but there's also the water of teaching programming.

00:35:56.340 --> 00:35:59.300
And we are so much in this one side water

00:35:59.300 --> 00:36:02.179
that we don't really even realize how weird it is.

00:36:02.179 --> 00:36:04.580
And there's some history in our field

00:36:04.580 --> 00:36:06.459
that many people aren't aware of

00:36:06.459 --> 00:36:09.860
that has also contributed to that philosophy.

00:36:09.860 --> 00:36:12.860
So who knows who this is, the creator of Logo?

00:36:15.540 --> 00:36:17.379
Yes, Seymour Papert.

00:36:17.379 --> 00:36:19.459
So he's kind of well known in our community.

00:36:19.459 --> 00:36:22.379
He created Logo, which was the first programming language

00:36:22.379 --> 00:36:26.320
for children, but he came rooted in a certain philosophy.

00:36:27.300 --> 00:36:29.560
He actually studied with a guy called Jean Piaget,

00:36:29.560 --> 00:36:31.760
one of the most important psychologists

00:36:31.760 --> 00:36:33.600
of the previous century.

00:36:33.600 --> 00:36:37.679
And he's the founder of a thing called constructivism.

00:36:37.679 --> 00:36:40.879
And constructivism means, the basic idea,

00:36:40.879 --> 00:36:43.080
there's a lot to it, but the basic idea is that

00:36:43.080 --> 00:36:45.840
I cannot put knowledge into your brain.

00:36:45.840 --> 00:36:47.679
The only way you can learn something

00:36:47.679 --> 00:36:52.520
is if you construct reality in your own brain.

00:36:52.520 --> 00:36:54.360
And Piaget said about Papert,

00:36:54.399 --> 00:36:58.159
nobody understands my work better than Seymour.

00:36:58.159 --> 00:37:01.479
He was very much influenced by this idea of,

00:37:01.479 --> 00:37:05.080
you cannot, you should not teach people things

00:37:05.080 --> 00:37:06.320
they should explore.

00:37:06.320 --> 00:37:08.560
So for example, he said things like,

00:37:08.560 --> 00:37:11.199
by explaining something to someone,

00:37:11.199 --> 00:37:15.919
you take away the opportunity for a child to discover it.

00:37:15.919 --> 00:37:18.139
And this being a bad thing,

00:37:18.139 --> 00:37:20.919
that you take away this opportunity.

00:37:20.919 --> 00:37:22.479
And then you see how weird this is

00:37:22.479 --> 00:37:25.919
if you compare this to other things.

00:37:25.919 --> 00:37:29.679
So imagine you have a kid or a kid you care for,

00:37:29.679 --> 00:37:33.040
they wanna learn the guitar or tennis.

00:37:33.959 --> 00:37:36.719
Would you buy them a guitar and say,

00:37:36.719 --> 00:37:38.300
hey, I'm not going to tell you anything

00:37:38.300 --> 00:37:40.600
because that will just ruin the surprise for you?

00:37:40.600 --> 00:37:44.719
So you just figure out, you know,

00:37:44.719 --> 00:37:48.280
strings, chords, finger placement,

00:37:48.280 --> 00:37:49.560
you just figure it out.

00:37:49.560 --> 00:37:51.600
You'll be fine, it'll be fun this way.

00:37:51.600 --> 00:37:52.639
I'll be in my room.

00:37:54.360 --> 00:37:57.320
Or like tennis, do you really want kids to figure out

00:37:57.320 --> 00:37:59.320
what is a backhand and a forehand

00:37:59.320 --> 00:38:01.199
and how do you rip the thing most efficiently?

00:38:01.199 --> 00:38:03.239
It doesn't make any sense.

00:38:03.239 --> 00:38:05.000
So then you see how weird it is

00:38:05.000 --> 00:38:09.280
and how very much that philosophy of Piaget and Papert

00:38:09.280 --> 00:38:12.199
still is visible in those programming books

00:38:12.199 --> 00:38:14.159
I showed at the beginning of my lecture.

00:38:14.159 --> 00:38:15.919
Because in this situation, we'd be like,

00:38:15.919 --> 00:38:17.760
we'd get them a tutor in a club.

00:38:18.639 --> 00:38:23.399
And that form of teaching is actually very common

00:38:23.399 --> 00:38:27.719
and very aligned with the left-hand side of the argument

00:38:27.719 --> 00:38:30.879
with phonics and with explanation and practice

00:38:30.879 --> 00:38:35.159
in all sorts of things, sports, music, language, math.

00:38:35.159 --> 00:38:38.959
We have focused on just explaining stuff to kids.

00:38:40.159 --> 00:38:42.879
So warning, some controversy ahead

00:38:42.879 --> 00:38:45.919
because some people really still very much

00:38:46.040 --> 00:38:48.679
buy into this philosophy.

00:38:48.679 --> 00:38:52.000
But across fields, it's been very, very clear

00:38:52.000 --> 00:38:55.760
that this left-hand side instruction phonics explaining

00:38:55.760 --> 00:38:56.919
is just better.

00:38:58.080 --> 00:39:00.040
It's just better than exploration.

00:39:00.040 --> 00:39:03.840
There's this paper by a Dutch psychologist

00:39:03.840 --> 00:39:05.959
called Paul Kirschner and some other people,

00:39:05.959 --> 00:39:07.919
why minimal guidance doesn't work.

00:39:07.919 --> 00:39:12.719
And it summarizes a long list of studies across fields

00:39:12.719 --> 00:39:16.800
saying you should just explain stuff to kids.

00:39:16.800 --> 00:39:19.479
There's this other paper actually by Sweller and Cooper

00:39:19.479 --> 00:39:22.000
that compares two groups of children.

00:39:22.000 --> 00:39:26.159
Half of the group got a worked example.

00:39:26.159 --> 00:39:28.840
So the teacher said, this is what you do

00:39:28.840 --> 00:39:31.159
and you just do the steps.

00:39:31.159 --> 00:39:35.040
And the other group of kids got a more traditional,

00:39:35.040 --> 00:39:37.120
maybe in some places, equation.

00:39:37.120 --> 00:39:38.199
They said, this is the equation

00:39:38.199 --> 00:39:39.360
and you have to solve it for A.

00:39:39.360 --> 00:39:41.320
And they didn't know how to do it.

00:39:41.360 --> 00:39:44.679
And they compared the children how well they did.

00:39:44.679 --> 00:39:48.000
And this left group, first group, did way better.

00:39:48.000 --> 00:39:51.639
They did the solutions in 1 5th of the time

00:39:51.639 --> 00:39:52.800
of the other group.

00:39:52.800 --> 00:39:56.600
So not 20% less in the 20% of the time.

00:39:56.600 --> 00:40:01.600
And they also did better on new programs, new problems.

00:40:01.600 --> 00:40:03.040
So it wasn't that they could just solve

00:40:03.040 --> 00:40:04.360
the thing they've practiced.

00:40:04.360 --> 00:40:06.719
If you then gave them similar assignments,

00:40:06.719 --> 00:40:07.879
they still did well.

00:40:08.840 --> 00:40:11.040
And this makes lots and lots of sense

00:40:11.719 --> 00:40:14.520
if you know a little bit about short-term memory.

00:40:14.520 --> 00:40:18.520
So here's another mandatory audience participation session.

00:40:18.520 --> 00:40:22.399
I'm going to put, let's say, $1,000 on the table.

00:40:22.399 --> 00:40:25.080
If you can remember this tiny snippet of things,

00:40:25.080 --> 00:40:27.239
I'll put in front of you for a few seconds.

00:40:28.320 --> 00:40:29.159
No pictures.

00:40:31.320 --> 00:40:33.439
Ah, that was hard, right?

00:40:33.439 --> 00:40:34.479
No one got it.

00:40:34.479 --> 00:40:35.639
I'm not really betting.

00:40:38.719 --> 00:40:39.560
Next one.

00:40:39.560 --> 00:40:40.840
So the next one is interesting.

00:40:41.639 --> 00:40:43.760
I wouldn't bet $1,000, but I would bet 100

00:40:43.760 --> 00:40:45.360
that this is still pretty hard.

00:40:49.320 --> 00:40:50.479
Next one.

00:40:50.479 --> 00:40:52.479
I wouldn't bet any money on this one.

00:40:55.120 --> 00:40:57.040
That's super easy, right?

00:40:57.040 --> 00:40:59.639
But it was the same length, the same number of things,

00:40:59.639 --> 00:41:01.479
the same variety in things.

00:41:01.479 --> 00:41:04.340
And still, this was super easy to do.

00:41:05.379 --> 00:41:07.959
That's because our short-term memory

00:41:07.959 --> 00:41:11.800
can only hold seven plus or minus two items.

00:41:11.800 --> 00:41:14.399
And actually, you might be aware of this study.

00:41:14.399 --> 00:41:17.439
Neural research said it's now four items.

00:41:17.439 --> 00:41:20.520
So there's very, very limited room

00:41:20.520 --> 00:41:23.600
in our brain to store things.

00:41:23.600 --> 00:41:25.560
And this, why is this so easy?

00:41:25.560 --> 00:41:27.959
Because you just store three things.

00:41:27.959 --> 00:41:30.479
You don't store the individual letters.

00:41:30.479 --> 00:41:33.320
You don't store the individual words.

00:41:33.320 --> 00:41:35.159
You store the concept.

00:41:35.159 --> 00:41:37.959
You think of a cat, and then of love, and of cake,

00:41:37.959 --> 00:41:39.639
and it makes sense.

00:41:39.639 --> 00:41:41.120
And if you think about this,

00:41:41.120 --> 00:41:43.699
you have room left in your brain.

00:41:43.699 --> 00:41:46.439
You can read this, memorize it, and think,

00:41:46.439 --> 00:41:47.800
oh, I miss my cat.

00:41:47.800 --> 00:41:49.080
Oh, I would love some cake.

00:41:49.080 --> 00:41:51.159
Maybe there will be cake at the coffee break later,

00:41:51.159 --> 00:41:54.320
while still also remembering these three things.

00:41:54.320 --> 00:41:55.320
You can do that.

00:41:56.679 --> 00:42:00.560
So that has to do with something called cognitive load.

00:42:00.560 --> 00:42:03.679
If I would really bet you to remember this,

00:42:03.679 --> 00:42:05.840
then if you were to try memorizing it,

00:42:05.840 --> 00:42:08.159
you get this fullness in your brain, right?

00:42:08.159 --> 00:42:10.040
You're like, oh, it's an O with a dot,

00:42:10.040 --> 00:42:12.959
and a long stripe, and like a sigma, but reverse.

00:42:12.959 --> 00:42:15.439
You feel your brain getting fuller.

00:42:15.439 --> 00:42:18.659
And that fullness is called cognitive load.

00:42:19.800 --> 00:42:22.360
And that's the reason that this one group,

00:42:22.360 --> 00:42:23.840
the left group, does better,

00:42:23.840 --> 00:42:26.679
and in all sort of similar experiments,

00:42:26.679 --> 00:42:30.679
because the other group had a too high of a cognitive load.

00:42:30.679 --> 00:42:31.899
They're solving the problem,

00:42:31.899 --> 00:42:33.439
but they have to think of many things,

00:42:34.199 --> 00:42:35.399
like what approach am I going to take,

00:42:35.399 --> 00:42:37.679
and oh, what is that technique again?

00:42:37.679 --> 00:42:39.679
And their brain gets so full

00:42:39.679 --> 00:42:43.360
that there's no more room to actually store the memory

00:42:43.360 --> 00:42:44.719
of what they were doing.

00:42:46.179 --> 00:42:47.959
So I think the biggest,

00:42:47.959 --> 00:42:50.500
if you just remember one thing from my talk,

00:42:50.500 --> 00:42:55.500
is you don't become an expert by doing expert things.

00:42:55.760 --> 00:42:58.000
That's what these studies have shown.

00:42:58.000 --> 00:43:00.699
And that's the misconception that we have in programming,

00:43:00.699 --> 00:43:02.879
and to a certain extent, also in math.

00:43:02.919 --> 00:43:06.280
We think that if we want kids to be problem solvers,

00:43:06.280 --> 00:43:08.239
we give them problems to solve.

00:43:08.239 --> 00:43:10.120
If we want kids to be programmers,

00:43:10.120 --> 00:43:12.199
we give them programs to program.

00:43:12.199 --> 00:43:14.360
But it doesn't work like this.

00:43:14.360 --> 00:43:16.080
If you want kids to be problem solvers,

00:43:16.080 --> 00:43:18.600
you have to teach them to memorize

00:43:18.600 --> 00:43:21.199
a lot of strategies for problem solving,

00:43:21.199 --> 00:43:23.600
or a lot of strategies for programming.

00:43:23.600 --> 00:43:25.360
That's how they memorize.

00:43:25.360 --> 00:43:27.120
And then once they see a problem,

00:43:27.120 --> 00:43:28.639
their long-term memory is filled

00:43:28.639 --> 00:43:32.159
with all of these approaches they can then use.

00:43:32.159 --> 00:43:35.120
Again, think of other things you want to learn,

00:43:35.120 --> 00:43:36.199
like running.

00:43:36.199 --> 00:43:38.600
The worst way to prepare for a marathon

00:43:38.600 --> 00:43:40.280
is to run a marathon every day.

00:43:41.360 --> 00:43:42.399
Everyone gets that.

00:43:42.399 --> 00:43:43.600
What do you do?

00:43:43.600 --> 00:43:46.280
Well, you do bench presses, and sit-ups,

00:43:46.280 --> 00:43:47.439
and interval training.

00:43:47.439 --> 00:43:51.399
You do all these other things that help you do a marathon.

00:43:51.399 --> 00:43:53.919
Same with playing the violin.

00:43:53.919 --> 00:43:56.679
If you want to learn some sort of Beethoven thing,

00:43:56.679 --> 00:44:00.719
you're not going to start by doing exactly that thing.

00:44:00.760 --> 00:44:03.199
No, you'll do chords and finger placement

00:44:03.199 --> 00:44:04.280
and stuff like that.

00:44:04.280 --> 00:44:06.639
So you build up little pieces of knowledge

00:44:06.639 --> 00:44:09.159
such that you can achieve bigger things.

00:44:09.159 --> 00:44:12.479
So you don't become an expert by doing expert things.

00:44:12.479 --> 00:44:14.760
And in programming, we still very much believe that.

00:44:14.760 --> 00:44:17.439
So my goal of this is to start a fight,

00:44:17.439 --> 00:44:19.879
well, not a fight, but a debate

00:44:19.879 --> 00:44:21.800
about pedagogy of programming.

00:44:21.800 --> 00:44:24.639
Because this site,

00:44:24.639 --> 00:44:27.320
this whole language inquiry exploration part,

00:44:27.320 --> 00:44:30.600
is basically the only site that we have heard from

00:44:31.479 --> 00:44:34.080
in programming, partly stemming from Papert and Logo,

00:44:34.080 --> 00:44:37.320
partly coming from the way we were taught in the 80s.

00:44:38.239 --> 00:44:39.600
We have that site covered,

00:44:39.600 --> 00:44:42.840
but now I want to explore the other side.

00:44:42.840 --> 00:44:46.639
How would direct instruction look like for programming?

00:44:46.639 --> 00:44:49.399
What are those tiny things that we can do

00:44:49.399 --> 00:44:51.719
to help kids become programmers?

00:44:51.719 --> 00:44:54.679
What are the interval trainings, and the bench presses,

00:44:54.679 --> 00:44:57.639
and the chords of programming?

00:44:57.639 --> 00:44:59.479
We've been exploring this, actually,

00:44:59.479 --> 00:45:01.199
at my research group in Leiden.

00:45:01.199 --> 00:45:03.399
And one of the cool things that we've done,

00:45:03.399 --> 00:45:05.560
probably the most exciting thing,

00:45:05.560 --> 00:45:08.080
maybe next to the Enron case that I've worked on,

00:45:08.080 --> 00:45:13.000
is this idea that we can teach kids to say syntax,

00:45:13.000 --> 00:45:15.800
to vocalize syntax aloud.

00:45:15.800 --> 00:45:20.159
Remember that sound really matters

00:45:20.159 --> 00:45:22.159
for English and other languages.

00:45:22.159 --> 00:45:26.840
So probably code sounds also matter a lot.

00:45:26.840 --> 00:45:29.239
And we did an experiment with some novices,

00:45:30.000 --> 00:45:32.800
and we asked them to speak a line of code aloud,

00:45:32.800 --> 00:45:35.600
simple things like an assignment.

00:45:35.600 --> 00:45:37.080
We got all sorts of things.

00:45:37.080 --> 00:45:40.159
X is five, X equals five, X gets five,

00:45:40.159 --> 00:45:42.800
set X to five, assign five to X.

00:45:42.800 --> 00:45:45.959
All sensible things, but apparently kids,

00:45:45.959 --> 00:45:49.000
and we repeated it with experts, same story,

00:45:49.000 --> 00:45:50.719
we don't have a shared mental model

00:45:50.719 --> 00:45:53.600
of how to read code in our heads.

00:45:53.600 --> 00:45:56.800
And probably based on those stuff we know from linguistics,

00:45:56.800 --> 00:45:59.800
this is going to hamper our understanding.

00:45:59.800 --> 00:46:01.840
And something interesting that we didn't think about,

00:46:01.840 --> 00:46:03.719
so we thought it was going to be confusing,

00:46:03.719 --> 00:46:05.280
but these were Dutch children,

00:46:05.280 --> 00:46:06.879
and there were all these extra things

00:46:06.879 --> 00:46:10.040
that came into play that we didn't think of.

00:46:10.040 --> 00:46:13.919
For example, this letter in English is called I,

00:46:13.919 --> 00:46:17.520
I as in tie, but in Dutch, my native language

00:46:17.520 --> 00:46:19.439
and the native language of these kids,

00:46:19.439 --> 00:46:22.040
we say it as E, E as in creep.

00:46:23.000 --> 00:46:26.280
So once children started reading these code snippets,

00:46:26.280 --> 00:46:28.199
they got confusing information,

00:46:28.199 --> 00:46:31.479
because the teacher would often say for I in range,

00:46:31.479 --> 00:46:33.679
because your brain gets in the English mode,

00:46:33.679 --> 00:46:35.479
but sometimes also conversationally,

00:46:35.479 --> 00:46:38.280
the teacher would say, oh, what variable, oh, it's E,

00:46:38.280 --> 00:46:40.560
because they would be speaking in Dutch at that point.

00:46:40.560 --> 00:46:43.360
So we had kids vocalize this code snippet

00:46:43.360 --> 00:46:48.360
as for I in range, print E, same code snippet.

00:46:48.399 --> 00:46:52.360
So then you can wonder, have they really understood?

00:46:52.360 --> 00:46:54.639
So one of the things that we're working on

00:46:54.679 --> 00:46:57.800
is this model of, we need consistent vocalization

00:46:57.800 --> 00:47:01.199
for source code such that children can repeat it

00:47:01.199 --> 00:47:02.679
and memorize it better.

00:47:02.679 --> 00:47:06.560
We did a super cool study where we had a group of kids

00:47:06.560 --> 00:47:10.959
repeating source code after us, for I in range,

00:47:10.959 --> 00:47:12.320
very much like you would do the tables

00:47:12.320 --> 00:47:14.280
of multiplication as well.

00:47:14.280 --> 00:47:16.959
One times three is three.

00:47:16.959 --> 00:47:18.760
And we found out it actually helps.

00:47:18.760 --> 00:47:22.719
We had two groups, one group read code aloud every lesson,

00:47:22.719 --> 00:47:24.760
and we had a control group that didn't do that.

00:47:24.760 --> 00:47:26.320
We would vocalize the code,

00:47:26.320 --> 00:47:28.520
but we didn't have this group exercise

00:47:28.520 --> 00:47:30.399
of vocalizing everything.

00:47:30.399 --> 00:47:32.080
And we found out that this first group

00:47:32.080 --> 00:47:35.280
just does a lot better on syntax exercises,

00:47:35.280 --> 00:47:38.080
and we're about to publish a paper on that.

00:47:38.080 --> 00:47:41.040
And it's so cool because if I give presentations

00:47:41.040 --> 00:47:43.439
about this research to elementary school teachers

00:47:43.439 --> 00:47:47.560
that I sometimes do, they look at me like, wow,

00:47:47.560 --> 00:47:50.040
it's 2019 and you've just figured out

00:47:50.040 --> 00:47:55.040
that having children read something aloud works?

00:47:57.159 --> 00:48:01.479
Well done, slow clap, very impressive.

00:48:01.479 --> 00:48:04.959
They're like, did no one ever think of this?

00:48:04.959 --> 00:48:07.879
We all go to school saying one times three.

00:48:07.879 --> 00:48:09.120
How often have you done that?

00:48:09.120 --> 00:48:12.120
How often were you made to read aloud letters

00:48:12.120 --> 00:48:13.679
when you were learning?

00:48:13.679 --> 00:48:16.120
And yet, to the best of our knowledge,

00:48:16.120 --> 00:48:18.679
we're the first one to actually try this on source code,

00:48:18.679 --> 00:48:21.399
and surprise, surprise, it actually worked.

00:48:21.399 --> 00:48:22.679
So no one was really surprised.

00:48:22.679 --> 00:48:25.000
So that's one of the things we're doing.

00:48:25.000 --> 00:48:28.080
Another thing that we're doing is teaching children

00:48:28.080 --> 00:48:32.399
and students as well, explicit reading strategies.

00:48:32.399 --> 00:48:36.639
So here's a snippet from a linguistics paper that says,

00:48:36.639 --> 00:48:40.399
here are a few strategies that you can use

00:48:40.399 --> 00:48:42.439
to read natural language.

00:48:42.439 --> 00:48:45.780
So a strategy is like looking at pictures,

00:48:45.780 --> 00:48:48.899
skipping parts of the text that you think are important.

00:48:49.820 --> 00:48:53.100
They explain children how to read natural language

00:48:53.100 --> 00:48:56.100
if they are just learning, and then they test them.

00:48:56.100 --> 00:48:58.300
They say, what strategy have you used?

00:48:58.300 --> 00:49:00.659
Or they say, here's some natural language,

00:49:00.659 --> 00:49:03.620
use this specific strategy,

00:49:03.620 --> 00:49:06.139
and then try to figure out what it means.

00:49:06.139 --> 00:49:08.060
We don't do any of this for source code.

00:49:08.060 --> 00:49:10.979
I have undergrads in programming classes,

00:49:10.979 --> 00:49:13.540
you give them a piece of source code to read,

00:49:13.540 --> 00:49:15.379
and they just start at the beginning.

00:49:16.219 --> 00:49:17.179
And why wouldn't they?

00:49:17.179 --> 00:49:19.580
We've never told them what is a good strategy

00:49:19.580 --> 00:49:22.139
for reading code, things experts do,

00:49:22.139 --> 00:49:23.620
because they've picked it up naturally,

00:49:23.620 --> 00:49:26.459
like look at all the methods, or look at all the fields,

00:49:26.459 --> 00:49:27.500
or collapse something.

00:49:27.500 --> 00:49:29.219
Some IDEs can collapse everything,

00:49:29.219 --> 00:49:31.699
and then you just look at the signatures.

00:49:31.699 --> 00:49:32.899
They have no strategies

00:49:32.899 --> 00:49:34.419
because they weren't taught strategies.

00:49:34.419 --> 00:49:36.300
And we did a study, actually,

00:49:36.300 --> 00:49:38.120
this is still research in progress,

00:49:38.120 --> 00:49:39.820
but we had, these were undergrads.

00:49:39.820 --> 00:49:43.340
Some students, we explained strategies,

00:49:43.340 --> 00:49:45.699
we practiced strategies with them in class,

00:49:46.520 --> 00:49:47.939
and we had a control group that were taught

00:49:47.939 --> 00:49:48.979
in a more traditional way,

00:49:48.979 --> 00:49:50.899
so very much aimed at creating programs,

00:49:50.899 --> 00:49:52.419
and not really reading a lot.

00:49:52.419 --> 00:49:54.540
Surprise, surprise, guess not, the group,

00:49:54.540 --> 00:49:57.659
where we explicitly explained reading strategies

00:49:57.659 --> 00:49:59.540
for source code, they did better.

00:49:59.540 --> 00:50:03.060
This is, as I said, still research in progress.

00:50:03.060 --> 00:50:05.860
And something else that we're really excited about

00:50:05.860 --> 00:50:07.820
is assessment.

00:50:07.820 --> 00:50:08.939
In programming classes,

00:50:08.939 --> 00:50:11.899
especially in programming clubs for kids,

00:50:11.899 --> 00:50:13.520
assessment plays no role,

00:50:13.520 --> 00:50:15.479
because they're very much ran by these

00:50:16.260 --> 00:50:19.219
people that buy into the exploratory learning style.

00:50:19.219 --> 00:50:21.520
So things like this,

00:50:23.159 --> 00:50:26.040
having a tiny test saying, this is in Dutch,

00:50:26.040 --> 00:50:28.399
which one is a variable, circle the right block,

00:50:28.399 --> 00:50:30.879
or which one sets a variable to zero,

00:50:30.879 --> 00:50:33.159
doing these things in code clubs

00:50:33.159 --> 00:50:36.540
is very much against what they believe in.

00:50:36.540 --> 00:50:38.540
So that's something we're exploring.

00:50:38.540 --> 00:50:42.459
How can we get assessments into out-of-school code clubs?

00:50:42.459 --> 00:50:44.959
Not because we want to give kids grades,

00:50:45.439 --> 00:50:48.020
because we want to help teachers understand

00:50:48.020 --> 00:50:50.060
what is the level that the children are at.

00:50:50.060 --> 00:50:51.899
Are they at this flat skill level

00:50:51.899 --> 00:50:53.679
where they maybe need a little bit of help

00:50:53.679 --> 00:50:54.899
to jump to the new level?

00:50:54.899 --> 00:50:57.219
So this is also something we're exploring.

00:50:57.219 --> 00:51:00.780
Should you run a code club on the site,

00:51:00.780 --> 00:51:02.659
then please send me an email or a tweet,

00:51:02.659 --> 00:51:04.280
because we'd be really interested

00:51:04.280 --> 00:51:06.379
if you want to try this stuff out with us.

00:51:07.260 --> 00:51:09.699
So, like everywhere, there are also haters

00:51:09.699 --> 00:51:11.919
in my new field, sadly.

00:51:12.879 --> 00:51:14.219
Because haters are everywhere

00:51:14.219 --> 00:51:16.120
except from knitting and running.

00:51:17.879 --> 00:51:21.300
So now I give this talk, now I go still to conferences

00:51:21.300 --> 00:51:23.199
because I just like being on a stage

00:51:23.199 --> 00:51:25.580
and I tell people this story, and they're like,

00:51:25.580 --> 00:51:27.979
but it doesn't seem fun.

00:51:27.979 --> 00:51:29.540
At one of the other conferences I presented

00:51:29.540 --> 00:51:32.260
something like this, a guy, they're often guys,

00:51:32.260 --> 00:51:36.939
pointed a finger in my face, almost saying,

00:51:36.939 --> 00:51:39.379
you're making it like school.

00:51:39.560 --> 00:51:43.879
No, school is not terrible.

00:51:43.879 --> 00:51:46.919
I'm teaching people things.

00:51:46.919 --> 00:51:48.719
I don't know, is school bad?

00:51:48.719 --> 00:51:52.760
I work at a school, calm down.

00:51:52.760 --> 00:51:56.060
But actually the nice thing is research says

00:51:56.060 --> 00:51:58.199
this doesn't matter.

00:51:58.199 --> 00:52:03.199
Stuff doesn't have to be fun to actually be useful.

00:52:04.239 --> 00:52:07.120
Like I go to this running club every Monday

00:52:07.120 --> 00:52:08.520
and I do 50 pushups.

00:52:08.540 --> 00:52:10.179
Do you think that's fun?

00:52:10.179 --> 00:52:13.739
No, being on my couch, watching Netflix

00:52:13.739 --> 00:52:16.459
and eating potato chips is fun.

00:52:16.459 --> 00:52:19.979
That is pain, it's horror, I dread it.

00:52:19.979 --> 00:52:23.459
But I know it makes me better and that's why I do it.

00:52:23.459 --> 00:52:25.100
And the same is true for kids.

00:52:25.100 --> 00:52:28.780
People think, especially educators, many educators

00:52:28.780 --> 00:52:31.379
and outside of school clubs think

00:52:31.379 --> 00:52:35.100
that if kids are just motivated, they will get skills.

00:52:35.100 --> 00:52:38.219
If they just wanna learn, then they will get better.

00:52:38.899 --> 00:52:39.739
But it's not true.

00:52:39.739 --> 00:52:42.320
It's actually very often the other way around.

00:52:42.320 --> 00:52:45.280
Kids that are skilled will be motivated.

00:52:45.280 --> 00:52:48.360
And specifically, like in my running exercise,

00:52:48.360 --> 00:52:52.080
if I feel I'm making progress, this also holds for kids.

00:52:52.080 --> 00:52:55.560
If they feel they're learning, even if it's painful,

00:52:55.560 --> 00:52:58.080
then they will be motivated to learn more.

00:52:58.080 --> 00:53:00.840
So what is actually kind of demotivating

00:53:00.840 --> 00:53:03.280
is just having them have fun and being stuck

00:53:03.280 --> 00:53:05.879
at a certain skill level because if they don't feel

00:53:05.879 --> 00:53:09.020
they're making progress, they will not be motivated.

00:53:09.020 --> 00:53:12.860
So that's it, that's everything I wanted to share.

00:53:12.860 --> 00:53:16.659
Before we end the session, let me summarize my entire talk

00:53:16.659 --> 00:53:19.419
in like one minute because I know some people came in late

00:53:19.419 --> 00:53:22.580
or they're just awake and also I speak a bit quickly.

00:53:22.580 --> 00:53:24.659
So let me give you a second chance

00:53:24.659 --> 00:53:27.219
to get the gist of everything.

00:53:27.219 --> 00:53:30.780
First of all, don't be this people.

00:53:32.500 --> 00:53:35.419
I know probably in this community,

00:53:35.919 --> 00:53:38.320
I've been at a conference since Tuesday.

00:53:38.320 --> 00:53:39.360
It's really friendly.

00:53:39.360 --> 00:53:41.679
I don't think lots of you need this advice,

00:53:41.679 --> 00:53:45.020
but still be aware of it and if you hear people do it,

00:53:45.020 --> 00:53:48.199
even if it's not you, try to step in

00:53:48.199 --> 00:53:53.199
and let's just try not to be or allow these people in.

00:53:54.080 --> 00:53:56.239
So what I've been talking about is

00:53:56.239 --> 00:53:59.840
the way we teach programming, which has been very influenced

00:53:59.840 --> 00:54:04.760
by streams of belief and often influenced

00:54:04.820 --> 00:54:09.379
by the lack of our community of a shared memory

00:54:09.379 --> 00:54:11.379
of how a programming lesson looks like

00:54:11.379 --> 00:54:13.540
that impedes us from teaching.

00:54:13.540 --> 00:54:17.179
And this culture is very valid in books and lessons.

00:54:17.179 --> 00:54:20.739
They very much emphasize problem solving and making fun

00:54:20.739 --> 00:54:24.020
and programming should be enjoyable and puzzly.

00:54:24.020 --> 00:54:27.179
And this comes to a certain extent also from the history

00:54:27.179 --> 00:54:30.580
of programming education that many people aren't aware of

00:54:30.600 --> 00:54:34.000
and that is very, very tied to a specific methodology

00:54:34.000 --> 00:54:35.280
of teaching.

00:54:35.280 --> 00:54:39.139
Sadly, this methodology just has shown in other fields

00:54:39.139 --> 00:54:42.020
consistently to not work as well

00:54:42.020 --> 00:54:43.840
as explanation and practice.

00:54:43.840 --> 00:54:48.840
So my new goal in life is to help figure programming out

00:54:49.600 --> 00:54:51.679
how could direct instruction look like?

00:54:51.679 --> 00:54:55.120
What are the tiny building blocks that we can give children

00:54:55.120 --> 00:54:59.159
so they advance and they're not swimming and confused,

00:54:59.179 --> 00:55:01.459
but they can feel they're making progress

00:55:01.459 --> 00:55:03.939
and thus be really motivated.

00:55:03.939 --> 00:55:04.780
The end.

00:55:04.780 --> 00:55:06.500
So if you wanna check out more of my work,

00:55:06.500 --> 00:55:08.459
I'm on Twitter and I have a website

00:55:08.459 --> 00:55:10.179
where all my research is shared,

00:55:10.179 --> 00:55:12.300
all my papers are there, open access,

00:55:12.300 --> 00:55:14.860
and always accompanied by a blog post

00:55:14.860 --> 00:55:17.500
that also educators could easily understand.

00:55:17.500 --> 00:55:19.800
So not too technical, no p-values there.

00:55:20.820 --> 00:55:22.260
If you like listening to me,

00:55:22.260 --> 00:55:24.939
you might also wanna check out a podcast I host.

00:55:24.939 --> 00:55:26.360
It's called SE Radio.

00:55:26.360 --> 00:55:27.979
We have five episodes every month

00:55:27.979 --> 00:55:31.360
interviewing people in the software engineering field.

00:55:32.800 --> 00:55:35.600
We don't do Q&A, but there's one question I always get,

00:55:35.600 --> 00:55:36.919
so I will answer it.

00:55:36.919 --> 00:55:39.139
Have you hand-drawn these slides?

00:55:39.139 --> 00:55:40.120
The answer is yes.

00:55:40.120 --> 00:55:42.520
I made them with my Apple Pencil

00:55:42.520 --> 00:55:45.199
and an app called GoodNotes,

00:55:45.199 --> 00:55:48.520
all by hand apart from some technology.

00:55:48.520 --> 00:55:51.280
And then I wouldn't wanna end before thanking

00:55:51.280 --> 00:55:53.040
some people that worked on this with me,

00:55:53.040 --> 00:55:55.439
mainly grad students and postdocs in my lab.

00:55:55.439 --> 00:55:57.239
And the final Greg, you know him

00:55:57.260 --> 00:55:58.459
because he's Greg Wilson

00:55:58.459 --> 00:56:00.419
and he's been just such an inspiration.

00:56:00.419 --> 00:56:01.260
Thank you.

